<ns2944:section xmlns:ns2944="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.concepts.architecture.mda.introduction.whatIsMda">

  <ns2945:title xmlns:ns2945="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">What is MDA?</ns2945:title>
  <ns2946:para xmlns:ns2946="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    MDA is  an approach suggested
    by the OMG for separating the architecture of an application from its implementation.
  </ns2946:para>
  <ns2947:para xmlns:ns2947="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    It requires that a PIM (<ns2948:emphasis xmlns:ns2948="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Platform Independent Model</ns2948:emphasis>) is generated
    first after which standard technology specific mappings are used to generate a
    <ns2949:emphasis xmlns:ns2949="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Platform Specific Model</ns2949:emphasis> (PSM).
  </ns2947:para>
  <ns2950:para xmlns:ns2950="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Many teams have followed such an approach intuitively, though the boundary between the
    platform independent and platform specific models has usually been fuzzy. The MDA
    <ns2951:emphasis xmlns:ns2951="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">formalizes this process and facilitates the development of MDA tools
    which drive this process</ns2951:emphasis>.
  </ns2950:para>
</ns2944:section>